“The Beauty Within” is a short film following sisters Aaraf (@aarafxadam) and Abrar Adam (@abrawrr) on their journey to find their individuality, voice, and strength. A film by @kanxsuda
✨ We interviewed Aaraf for film release, see link in bio. 🔗  These women embody the power of Black female heroism through their vulnerability and unity. The silent interaction between these sisters showcases the power and perseverance that lies within each of us— the beauty within. The film features ballerinas Sydnie Collins and Audrey Malek performing as guiding fairies, leading the main characters through their journey of self-identity. The audio throughout is a poem written to serve as a reminder that “ Black, Indigenous and women of color must always be present, visible and amplified.” - @aarafxadam

*Credits in the Comments*

🎞 by @wagatwe 💕 “A TikTok follower asked me to list the different types of feminisms. There’s no way I could do that, so I wanted to give a little #feminism101: what all feminisms have in common, how different ones are created, and why different labels *can* be helpful (even if they aren’t always).

I use Black feminism as a compass for my antirape work, but I still integrate other disciplines into my work: trauma theory, psychoanalytic theory, sociology...the list goes on!

Ultimately, it’s a way to combat ahistoricism by learning from great Black women before me, honoring their contributions to feminism, and building on their legacy.” (Posted with consent) 

#Blackfeminism #womanism #feministtheory #criticaltheory

The concept of “Man” and “Woman” are limiting. But it wasn’t always this way. 
 🎞 by #FeministAdvisor @corpusren “In the past and even today, many cultural groups recognized and made space for people and their identities based on the realities around them.”

“Unlike today where most EuroColonial influences are incorrectly based strictly on the invention of 2 genders and forcing people into those binaries. 

Some examples of nonbinary, gender fluid, two-spirit people are Hijras in India, Muxe in Mexico, the Bakla in the Philippines, the Machi healers in Chile and Argentina, Quariwarmi in Peru, and Fakaleiti (Tonga),Waria (Indonesia), Calabai, Calalai, and Bissu (Indonesia), Winkte (Lakota), and so many more. 

Some of these identities have existed before the introduction of colonization and continue today. Just as we have existed and will continue to exist.” (Posted with consent)

#nonbinary #education #colonization #gender #genderidentity

We caught up with @NadyaOkamoto the feminist founder behind It’s August, a new period product made for anyone who menstruates. She is dedicated to re-imagining and redefining the period experience to be powerful and dignified. Meet the author, organizer, and founder!  See link in bio for the full feature

“Every day I wake up feeling energized to continue this work to reimagine and redefine the period experience to be powerful.” – @nadyaokamoto

Q:  SINCE YOU FIRST LAUNCHED, HOW HAS IDENTITY, LANGUAGE, AND POLITICS SHAPED THE DIRECTION OF AUGUST?
NADYA : Everything about August was really shaped by our community -- and our community is a group of passionate young people who believe in the values that we stand by. Thus, their identity of being bold and curious and enthusiastic, is also reflected in August. Gender inclusivity is a huge component of our community, and why we recently co-built our gender inclusive period talk guide with our advisor, Schuyler Bailar. As I mentioned, our community has really become a space where we can talk about anything, and so politics and how we can reimagine how we talk about periods are very common topics you see our members discussing. You can go to our website itsaugust.co to check out and join our inner cycle community home on the Geneva app.

Honoring #DisabilityPrideMonth for our #ARTHERSTORY, curated by our platform art curator @amandabjorn 

Most of the world recognizes the work of renowned artist Frida Kahlo, but some may not know of the physical disabilities she lived with throughout her life. At the age of six, Frida was bedridden with polio causing damage to her right leg and foot, and left with a limp. As a teenager, she was in a severe tram accident leaving her spine and pelvis significantly damaged. With this intense recovery period, she began to paint. In the painting “The Broken Column” she depicts herself standing on the beach with her body open showing a rod and restrictive medical corset, which she had to wear for most of her life. Throughout her life, she confronted her disabilities and turned them into art. “I never paint dreams or nightmares. I paint my own reality.” Kahlo is a true inspiration for all of us! There is no marriage equality until people with disabilities can marry without losing benefits. 💭 by #FeministPartner @liberaljane ✨ “People with disabilities should have the right to marry without losing their income, benefits, or health insurance.

⭐️ In many countries, including the United States, Canada, and the United Kingdom, people with disabilities are discouraged from getting married or are pushed to divorce in order to get or maintain their income, benefits, and health insurance. 

📍 In the United States specifically, it's because benefits such as Supplemental Security Income (SSI) and Medicaid are needs-based and focus on current assets and income. When someone marries someone not in those programs, their partner's assets and income are combined with theirs. It is because of the combined income that many married people with disabilities lose their SSI and Medicaid benefits. For people with disabilities who are already married, many have been forced to divorce and live separately in order to keep benefits that they need to survive. 

⭐️ People with disabilities shouldn't be forced to choose between the benefits they need to survive and their partners. 🌙”
